        "title": "Null Object - Something to instantiate or singleton?",
        "body": "<p>This is more of a style question than an \"I'm having trouble question\". For Null placeholder objects (am I using the right term?), is it generally preferred to use the Singleton pattern? For ease of discussion, here's an example:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public interface Foo {\n    void myMethod();\n}\n\npublic class RealFoo implements Foo {\n    void myMethod() { /* Do something productive */ }\n}\n\npublic class MyUniverse {\n    public static void main(String args[]) {\n        Foo[] fooArray = new Foo[10];\n        // do something productive that might result in Null objects in the array\n        for (Foo f : fooArray) {\n            f.myMethod(); // I DONT WANT TO DO if (f != null) blah blah\n        }\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Ok so that's my scenario, is it preferred to do A or B?<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>// A\npublic class NullFoo implements Foo {\n    public NullFoo() {}       \n    public void myMethod() { /* don't need to do anything */ }\n}\n\n// B\npublic class NullFoo implements Foo {\n    private static NullFoo _instance = null;\n    protected NullFoo() {}\n    public static NullFoo getInstance() {\n        if (_instance == null) _instance = new NullFoo();\n        return _instance;\n    }\n    public void myMethod() {  /* don't need to do anything */ }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Thanks! My instinct that B is almost always superior but maybe I'm missing something, so I ask...<\/p>\n",
