            "last_activity_date": 1351004645,
            "creation_date": 1351004327,
            "body": "<p>I would go for the latter. I may be something of a trend-bucker on this, but I don't see singletons as inherently evil. If a class has no mutable state, a singleton is just fine.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'd make the constructor private, though, not protected.  Also, your lazy loading is race-prone; I would just instantiate NullFoo on the declaration line (<code>private static final Foo instance = new NullFoo();<\/code>). And lastly, don't forget to have the class actually implement the interface. :)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13033377,
            "question_id": 13033325,
            "last_edit_date": 1351004645
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/hRJwE.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1227237,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1192572,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1192572/smuco",
                "reputation": 117,
                "display_name": "smuco",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1351005743,
            "creation_date": 1351004527,
            "body": "<p>From the point of view of the virtual machine, it would be better the B solution as java would instantiate at most one object.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13033450,
            "question_id": 13033325,
            "last_edit_date": 1351005743
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2269841148c3f2ca251b8f2a2b995078?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 757313,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 758831,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/758831/wmorrison365",
                "reputation": 6378,
                "display_name": "wmorrison365",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1351004715,
            "creation_date": 1351004715,
            "body": "<p>Well, interesting. Can't say I've ever been faced with this but...<\/p>\n\n<p>I'd suggest if the instance is to be used consistently (i.e. it will always do the same thing) then go with B. That way, you have only a single shared instance representing your null object. This is a space-saving optimisation (rather than clutter your memory with <code>NullFoos<\/code>. Much the same as <code>Collections#emptyList<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>I must say though, in terms of dsign, I can't see why you'd <em>//do something productive that might result in Null objects in the array<\/em> which would take the <code>Foo<\/code> in your <code>fooArray<\/code> and then replace it with null. I'm sure you have your reasons though.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13033505,
            "question_id": 13033325
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/aLKQa.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 138128,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 342852,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/342852/sean-patrick-floyd",
                "reputation": 300632,
                "display_name": "Sean Patrick Floyd",
                "accept_rate": 97
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1351004574,
            "creation_date": 1351004574,
            "body": "<p>I'd implement the singleton as an enum.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>enum NullFoo implements Foo{\n  INSTANCE{\n    // implement methods here\n  }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>See: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singleton_pattern#The_Enum_way\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Singleton > The Enum Way<\/a> or read<br>\n<strong>Item 3:\nEnforce the singleton property with a private\nconstructor or an enum type<\/strong><br>\nin <a href=\"https://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/com/0321356683\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Effective Java 2nd Ed by Joshua Bloch<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13033462,
            "question_id": 13033325
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b3f88272379f2ca3fe4816afaabfdb06?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1763586,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1610015,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1610015/user1610015",
                "reputation": 6698,
                "display_name": "user1610015",
                "accept_rate": 86
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1351004754,
            "creation_date": 1351004754,
            "body": "<p>I think you shouldn't be using interfaces here. An interface describes a set of operations that a class that implements it is required to support. But you're using the NullFoo class to basically circumvent that requirement.<\/p>\n\n<p>So why not just use a base class that does nothing in its implementation of myMethod:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class BaseFoo\n{\n    public void myMethod()\n    {\n        // do nothing\n    }\n}\n\npublic class DerivedFoo extends BaseFoo\n{\n    public void myMethod()\n    {\n        // do actual work\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Or, if your actual situation does call for interfaces, then just go ahead and write the <code>if (foo != null) ...<\/code> tests.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13033519,
            "question_id": 13033325
        }
